      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Read all safety warnings and instructions before use.</strong> Failure to follow the
        warnings and instructions may result in electric shock, fire, and/or serious injury. Save all
        warnings and instructions for future reference.
      </div>

      <h3>Required Personal Safety Equipment</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Face mask</li>
        <li>Safety gloves</li>
        <li>Ear protection</li>
        <li>Safety glasses</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Work Area Safety</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Keep the work area clean and well lit. Cluttered or dark areas invite accidents.</li>
        <li>Do not operate in explosive atmospheres or in the presence of flammable liquids, gases, or dust &mdash; the tool creates sparks.</li>
        <li>Keep children and bystanders away while operating.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Electrical Safety</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>The plug must match the outlet. Never modify the plug or use adapter plugs.</li>
        <li>Avoid body contact with grounded surfaces such as pipes, radiators, ranges, and refrigerators.</li>
        <li>Do not expose the tool to rain or wet conditions.</li>
        <li>Do not abuse the cord; never use it for carrying, pulling, or unplugging the tool. Keep it away from heat, oil, sharp edges, and moving parts.</li>
        <li>Outdoors, use an extension cord suitable for outdoor use.</li>
        <li>If operating in a damp location is unavoidable, use a residual current device (RCD) protected supply.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Personal Safety</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Stay alert; do not operate while tired or under the influence of drugs, alcohol, or medication.</li>
        <li>Always wear eye protection and appropriate protective equipment.</li>
        <li>Prevent unintentional starting &mdash; ensure the switch is off before connecting to power, picking up, or carrying the tool.</li>
        <li>Remove any adjusting key or wrench before turning the tool on.</li>
        <li>Do not overreach; keep proper footing and balance at all times.</li>
        <li>Do not wear loose clothing or jewelry. Keep hair, clothing, and gloves away from moving parts.</li>
        <li>If dust extraction and collection facilities are provided, ensure they are connected and properly used.</li>
        <li>Do not let familiarity with the tool lead to complacency. A careless action can cause severe injury in a fraction of a second.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Tool Use, Care, and Service</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Do not overload the tool. Use the correct tool for your application.</li>
        <li>Do not use the tool if the switch does not turn it on and off &mdash; it is dangerous and must be repaired.</li>
        <li>Disconnect from power before making adjustments, changing accessories, or storing.</li>
        <li>Store idle tools out of the reach of children and untrained users.</li>
        <li>Maintain the tool and accessories: check for misalignment, binding, breakage, or any condition that may affect operation. Repair before use if damaged.</li>
        <li>Keep handles and grasping surfaces dry, clean, and free from oil and grease.</li>
        <li>Have the tool serviced only by a qualified repair person using identical replacement parts.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Additional Safety Warnings</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Tool safety is granted only by using original Mirka backing pads.</li>
        <li>Read the Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS) for the work surface.</li>
        <li>If any hand or wrist discomfort is experienced, stop working and seek medical attention. Repetitive motion and overexposure to vibration can cause hand, wrist, and arm injury.</li>
        <li>The power supply socket and connector are non-IEC appliance couplers. Only use an original Mirka power supply cable (available from your Mirka dealer).</li>
        <li>Check the tool, backing pad, power cord, and fittings regularly for wear. Replace a damaged supply cable with an original Mirka cable.</li>
        <li>Clean or replace the dust extractor's collection bag daily &mdash; dust can be highly combustible.</li>
        <li>Always ensure the workpiece is firmly fixed in place.</li>
        <li>Keep hands clear of the spinning accessory during use.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Dust hazard:</strong> Some dust created by power sanding contains chemicals known to
        cause cancer, birth defects, or other reproductive harm &mdash; for example lead from
        lead-based paints, crystalline silica from masonry, and arsenic and chromium from treated
        lumber. Work in a well-ventilated area with approved safety equipment such as dust masks
        designed to filter microscopic particles.
      </div>

      <h2>Components</h2>
      <p>Per Figure 1, the DEOS II Delta 663X has the following controls and features:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lever</strong> &mdash; Variable-speed trigger; press to start, adjust position to control speed.</li>
        <li><strong>Multi-purpose LED</strong> &mdash; Status indicator (flashing green = ready, solid red = overload/overtemperature).</li>
        <li><strong>Wireless indication LED</strong> &mdash; Bluetooth status (blinking blue = active, solid = connected).</li>
        <li><strong>On/Off</strong> &mdash; Main power switch.</li>
        <li><strong>LED bar</strong> &mdash; Shows the selected maximum speed setting.</li>
        <li><strong>Speed+ / Speed&minus;</strong> &mdash; Maximum-speed adjustment buttons.</li>
        <li><strong>Hose connection</strong> &mdash; Swivel exhaust for vacuum dust extraction.</li>
        <li><strong>Backing pad</strong> &mdash; 100 &times; 152 &times; 152 mm delta net pad (Mirka code 8292663011).</li>
        <li><strong>Power cord</strong> &mdash; Rewireable 4.3 m, 100&ndash;120 V US (Mirka code MIE9017211).</li>
      </ul>

